<HEADLINE>
 Good afternoon, AM editors. 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Los Angeles Times-Washington Post News Service Budget for
morning papers of Wednesday, May 25, 1994. For questions about
stories, the day editor is John Cullicott at (202) 334-7666, and the
night editor is Michael J. Kaeser at (213) 237-7832.

 National:

   BOMBPLOT -- NEW YORK -- A federal judge sentences Muslim
fundamentalists to 240 years in prison each for the 1993 terrorist
bombing of the World Trade Center that killed six people and injured
more than 1,000. Developing.

   DENNYS -- WASHINGTON -- Justice Department officials and the Denny's
restaurant chain announce a $45 million settlement of a discrimination
case that evoked a modern version of the lunchcounter protests of the
civil rights movement's early days. Developing.

   RADIATION -- WASHINGTON -- The Energy Department warns hundreds of
current and former workers at the Rocky Flats nuclear plant that they
were exposed to higher levels of radiation that originally calculated
from 1953 to 1967. Developing, by William Claiborne (Post).

   BENNETTS -- WASHINGTON -- While Robert S. Bennett has been hired to
defend President Clinton in his sexual harassment lawsuit, younger
brother Bill is deciding whether to seek the GOP nomination against
Clinton in 1996. 1,200 words, by Susan Page (Newsday). Moved.

   TORNADO -- WICHITA FALLS, Texas -- When the threat of tornadoes is a
way of life, each spring brings terrible possibilities; when the
funnel cloud forms, the people living in Tornado Alley know to lie low
and wait. 1,050 words, by Sue Anne Pressley (Post). Moved.

 International:

   SAFRICA -- CAPE TOWN, South Africa -- President Nelson Mandela,
making his first state-of-the-nation address, pledges to right the
wrongs of apartheid by helping blacks obtain jobs and assures South
Africa's white minority of protection from retribution. Developing.

   HAITI -- JACMEL, Haiti -- Transport ships defying the U.N. embargo
carry supplies of gasoline to Haiti and unload the forbidden cargo,
all within sight of U.S. Navy and Coast Guard helicopters hovering
nearby. Developing.

   HAITI-POLICY -- WASHINGTON -- U.S. ships challenge vessels headed for
Haiti. Developing.

   MIDEAST -- JERICHO, West Bank -- PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat,
asserting Palestinian authority, cancels the military orders issued
during 27 years of Israeli occupation of Jericho and reinstates laws
in effect before the 1967 Middle East war. Developing.

   NATO -- BRUSSELS, Belgium -- NATO defense ministers consider Russia's
continued demand for special status as its condition for joining
NATO's Partnership for Peace; U.S. Defense Secretary William Perry
insists Russia will get no such privileges. Developing.

   BOSNIA-POLICY -- WASHINGTON -- The House considers two amendments to
lift the arms embargo on Bosnian Muslims. Developing.

 Financial:

   TRADE -- WASHINGTON -- Three months after U.S.-Japanese ties stumbled
to a new low point, negotiators on both sides agree to resume trade
talks, with White House officials painting a bright picture.
Developing.

   TURNER -- Ted Turner is spending liberally to turn his World
Championship Wrestling into a serious challenger to the World
Wrestling Federation; Turner is even trying to lure wrestling legend
Hulk Hogan back into action. 600 words, by Alan Citron (Times). Moved.

