<HEADLINE>
 New Attorney General Shakes Up Federal Police (Mexico City) 
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Just 10 days after taking office, Mexico's new
attorney general Tuesday announced a radical reorganization of the
Federal Judicial Police, starting with the firing of five top
commanders and the elimination of special details within the force.
</P>
<P>
The actions were taken, according to a statement from Attorney
General Humberto Benitez's office, ``to make the force more efficient
and to avoid illegal activities.''
</P>
<P>
Mexican police at all levels have come under increasing pressure in
the past year to restore public order in the wake of the unsolved
assassinations of a Roman Catholic cardinal, the leading presidential
candidate and the Tijuana police chief, in addition to a wave of
kidnappings and audacious gun battles between rival narcotics gangs.
</P>
<P>
Benitez cracked down especially hard on the department in charge of
investigations, eliminating it and firing its five commanders.
</P>
</TEXT>
