<HEADLINE>
 Good morning, PM editors.
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Los Angeles Times-Washington Post News Service budget for
afternoon papers of Wednesday, May 25, 1994. For questions about
stories, the PM editor is Stan Roberts in Los Angeles at (800)
283-NEWS, ext. 77832 or (213) 237-7832.

 International:

   RWANDA-REBELS -- RWAMAGANA, Rwanda -- Some of them are only boys, 14
or 15 years old, but the rebels of the Rwandan Patriotic Front have
proved themselves a more disciplined, organized military force than
the Rwandan army and claim loftier ideals than similar rebel movements
in other African countries. 900 words, by David Lamb (Times). Moved.

   MIDEAST-FAMILY -- GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip -- The Danaf family's complex
story is the tale of the splintered and often confusing relationships
that typify Gazan families, of lifetimes of desperation and fading
hope now turned to bittersweet joy. 1,300 words, by Mark Fineman
(Times). New. With MIDEAST-TIMES, MIDEAST-POST and MIDEAST-NDY, all
moved.

   HAITI-TIMES (2ndld) -- JACMEL, Haiti -- Flaunting the sieve-like
embargo enacted by the United Nations, ships sail into the port of
Jacmel under the noses of blockading vessels and unload their cargoes,
mostly of gasoline. 750 words, by Kenneth Freed (Times). With
HAITI-POST, both moved.

   MEXICO-COLOSIO -- LOS ANGELES -- Newly reunited family members of the
accused assassin of Mexican presidential candidate Luis Donaldo
Colosio have given a potentially explosive new account of the case
that implicates two Mexican federal security officials, family
representatives say. 610 words, by Patrick J. McDonnell and Sebastian
Rotella (Times). With MEXICO, both moved.

   CHINA-POLICY-NDY -- WASHINGTON -- Presidential candidate Bill Clinton
vowed he would punish Chinese leaders by revoking China's preferential
trading status if they failed to improve human rights; President
Clinton is just about to do the opposite. 720 words, by Glenn Kessler
(Newsday). With CHINA-POLICY-POST, both moved.

   VIET-POLICY -- WASHINGTON -- The Clinton administration has concluded
an agreement with the government of Vietnam that will open the way for
U.S. diplomats to represent and protect Vietnamese-Americans on
Vietnamese soil, U.S. officials say. 600 words, by Jim Mann (Times) .
Moved.

   BOSNIA-NIGHTMARE -- SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina -- Threats by
Western countries to pull U.N. troops out of embattled Bosnia have
stirred fears of devastating consequences; such a pullout could be
lopsided and would almost guarantee a widening of the war. 1,270
words, by Carol J. Williams (Times). New.

   CZECH -- PRAGUE, Czech Republic -- While former Communists and
Socialists in much of Eastern Europe are riding a popular backlash
against economic reforms to return to power, the Czech Republic
appears to be a notable exception. 1,120 words, by David B. Ottaway
(Post). Moved.

   NATO-TIMES -- BRUSSELS, Belgium -- Russia said it will join NATO's
Partnership for Peace Program for former East Bloc countries despite
its earlier reservations, but hinted that it still may seek some
political concessions in return. 730 words, by Art Pine (Times). With
NATO-POST, both moved.

   MACEDONIA -- SKOPJE, Macedonia -- To hear Macedonians on the streets
of their capital talk, the only ones suffering from the blockade
Greece has placed on this landlocked former Yugoslav republic are the
Greeks themselves. 850 words, by Steve Vogel (Post special). New.

 National:

   HEALTH-TIMES -- WASHINGTON -- With all five congressional committees
working on health care legislation certain to miss their self-imposed
Memorial Day deadline for producing bills, President Clinton will go
to Capitol Hill to prod them to finish their work. 740 words, by Karen
Tumulty (Times). With HEALTH-POST, both moved.

   WHITEWATER -- WASHINGTON -- Republican lawmakers step up pressure on
Democrats to schedule congressional hearings into the Whitewater
affair, as Special Counsel Robert B. Fiske Jr. winds down the initial
phase of his investigation of President Clinton's role in the failed
Arkansas land venture. 540 words, by Michael Ross (Times). Moved.

   ROSTY-TIMES -- Efforts to reach a plea bargain in the fraud case
against Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., intensify, with agreement no
longer hinging on keeping him out of jail; under discussion is how
much prison time would be recommended. 870 words, by Ronald J. Ostrow
and William J. Eaton (Times). With ROSTY-POST, both moved.

   BOMBPLOT-TIMES -- NEW YORK -- Shouting their defiance, four Islamic
militants are sentenced to life in prison without parole for last
year's bombing of the World Trade Center. 870 words, by Robert L.
Jackson (Times). With BOMBPLOT-POST and BOMBPLOT-NDY, all moved.

   CONTRACTOR -- WASHINGTON -- Four federal agencies are examining
allegations the Air Force was sold useless fighter cockpit displays by
a California defense contractor whose board members at the time
included William Perry and two other top Pentagon officials. 1,400
words, by Patrick J. Sloyan (Newsday). With CONTRACTOR-CASE, both
moved.

   BRIDES -- WASHINGTON -- A growing mail-order bridal bazaar has
sprouted since Soviet communism died; with Soviet emigration barriers
dismantled, about 350 Russian women entered the United States last
year as fiancees of American men. 870 words, by Kevin Sullivan (Post).
Moved.

   SCHIZOPHRENIA -- BALTIMORE -- Jumping into one of the liveliest
debates in psychiatry, researchers at the Johns Hopkins Medical
Institutions will investigate an unconventional theory that viruses or
other infectious agents trigger schizophrenia. 680 words, by Jonathan
Bor (Sun). Moved.

   PRESSER -- CLEVELAND -- Teamsters President Jackie Presser was one of
the most controversial union chiefs when he died in 1988, under
indictment on racketeering charges; a dispute over his $4.2 million
estate surfaces in state court and fifth wife Cynthia Presser has
admitted misusing hundreds of thousands of dollars from the estate and
violating her duties as its executor. 850 words, by Robert L. Jackson
(Times). New.

   SUITS -- WASHINGTON -- Federal bank and thrift regulators say $1.6
billion in claims against those who served failed banks and S Ls in
Texas and Virginia are at risk because of recent court rulings on the
deadline for bringing lawsuits, and they fear billions of dollars more
could be in jeopardy if other states set time limits on such cases.
1,060 words, by Sharon Walsh and Susan Schmidt (Post). Moved.

 Financial:

   PHONESEX -- HAGERSTOWN, Md. -- John Rebarick says he had no idea what
or where Sao Tome was until he got the most expensive geography lesson
of his life -- $3,500 in calls on a sex line patronized by his
roommate's girlfriend and apparently promoted by the foreign telephone
company. 920 words, by Michael Dresser (Sun). New.

   AIRPLANES -- To say the pickings have been slim of late for builders
of commercial airliners would be to exaggerate, but there may be help
on the horizon because of the slowly improving condition of the
airlines and because of something called the Airport Noise and
Capacity Act of 1990. 650 words, by Richard M. Weintraub (Post).
Moved.

