having a baby as an event full of rewards and moments of sheer
delight; but when the tears flow, it's often because society's
benchmark for when new mothers should be recovered -- six weeks to
eight weeks -- is unrealistic for many. 1,280 words, by Shari Roan
(Times) (l).

   HEALTH-PILL -- Dr. George Huggins, chairman of the department of
obstetrics and gynecology at Johns Hopkins Bayview Medical Center, one
of the institutions applying to serve as a test site for RU-486,
answers basic questions about the abortion drug. 975 words, by Linell
Smith (Sun) (l).

   HEALTH-PANIC -- Spontaneous panic attacks, once thought to be the
physical manifestation of inner angst, may instead be triggered by a
glitch in the body's respiratory system, according to a new study.
1,250 words, by Jamie Talan (Newsday). With HEALTH-PANIC-SIGNS (both
l).

   HEALTH-EAR -- Parents often wonder if they are doing the right thing
by choosing surgery to heal chronic ear infections, a procedure
criticized for being overused; guidelines in an article in the Journal
of the American Medical Association should help with the decision. 790
words, by Shari Roan (Times) (l).

   SCHIZOPHRENIA -- BALTIMORE -- Jumping into one of the liveliest
debates in psychiatry, researchers at the Johns Hopkins Medical
Institutions will investigate an unconventional theory that viruses or
other infectious agents trigger schizophrenia. 680 words, by Jonathan
Bor (Sun) (a). Moved.

   HEALTH-ON-CALL -- Dr. Simeon Margolis' mail-in clinic (Sun special)
(l).

   HEALTH-KIDS -- Drs. Modena Wilson and Alain Joffe tend to The
Younger Set (Sun special) (l).

   Consumers and personal finance:

   TRUSTS -- Creating the right trust can ensure the proper
distribution of an estate after death and keep the IRS from taking a
huge chunk away; Lisa Berger, author of a book about retirement
planning called ``Feathering Your Nest,'' recommends a Qualified
Terminable Interest Property Trust, or QTIP. 1,220 words, by Christine
Dugas (Newsday) (f).

   PHONESEX -- HAGERSTOWN, Md. -- John Rebarick says he had no idea what
or where Sao Tome was until he got the most expensive geography lesson
of his life -- $3,500 in calls on a sex line patronized by his
roommate's girlfriend and apparently promoted by the foreign telephone
company. 920 words, by Michael Dresser (Sun) (f). Moved.

   HIMOWITZ -- Fax modems provide two ways to transmit. By Michael
Himowitz (Evening Sun) (f).

   Lifestyle and people:

   FIRSTLADIES -- WASHINGTON -- WASHINGTON -- Three decades separate the
reigns of Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis and Hillary Rodham Clinton, and
no two women better illustrate the sea change in public perception of
the ``ideal woman.'' 1,150 words, by Elizabeth Shogren (Times) (l).

   BOOKSELLERS -- It's too costly, too important, too tiring, too
silly, too long or too short; it's the American Booksellers
Association's annual convention and trade exhibit, scheduled for this
weekend in Los Angeles. 810 words, by Paul D. Colford (Newsday) (l).

   BRIDES -- WASHINGTON -- A growing mail-order bridal bazaar has
sprouted since Soviet communism died; with Soviet emigration barriers
dismantled, about 350 Russian women entered the United States last
year as fiancees of American men. 870 words, by Kevin Sullivan (Post)
(a). Moved.

   GABRIEL -- Struggling in vain to be forever young. By Joyce Gabriel
(Stamford) (c).

   LITTWIN -- The Capriati descent should surprise no one. By Mike
Littwin (Sun) (c).

   MARTINEZ -- Ordeal at Charlie's Market shows how times have changed.
By Al Martinez (Times) (c).

   ROMANO -- Notes on newsmakers. By Lois Romano (Post) (w).

   WORDS -- Permit no usage breach to mar a perfect speech. By Rob Kyff
(Courant) (l)

   There is no COWHERD (Sun) feature today.

   Entertainment and the arts:

   FILM-SUMMER -- Hollywood is busy predicting which movies without big
expectations will become box-office hits, along the lines of last
summer's surprise hits, ``Free Willy'' and ``Sleepless in Seattle'';
while movies such as ``The Shadow'' are being touted, many really
don't qualify as sleeper candidates. 832 words, by Robert W. Welkos
(Times) (e).

   TV-FOX -- The Fox Broadcasting Co. announces a drama-heavy
prime-time lineup for fall in its latest bid to achieve parity with
CBS, ABC and NBC; in addition, Fox, known for its outpouring of series
featuring black performers, cancels five of them, including ``Roc,''
``South Central'' and ``In Living Color.'' 900 words, by Rick Du Brow
(Times) (e). Moved.

   TV-CABLE -- ``Biography,'' one of the more popular weekly shows on
the Arts Entertainment service, to run Monday through Friday nights;
other cable highlights. By Martie Zad (Post) (e). Weekend advance,
moved.

   HIRST -- Damien Hirst, London's leading chain-saw artist, hacks dead
livestock in half; his latest animal act is a lamb, all woolly and
cuddly-looking, floating in a white-framed tank of formaldehyde. 930
words, by Carl Schoettler (Sun) (e).

   RESTORATION -- HARTFORD, Conn. -- The increasingly dark, murky
appearance of the ``Crucifixion,'' a 17th century masterwork by the
great French painter Nicolas Poussin, has mystified visitors to the
Wadsworth Atheneum in recent years; now, once ghostly figures have
emerged from shadowy mists, thanks to a two-year conservation project.
1,250 words, by Owen McNally (Courant) (e).

   CLASSICS -- Conductor does justice to Shotakovich's 8th symphony. By
Stephen Wigler (Sun) (e).

   ROSENBERG -- TV's drama about blacks is all behind the scenes. By
Howard Rosenberg (Times) (e).

   TV-CARMODY -- John Carmody on TV (Post) (e).

   TV-PICKS -- Selecting the best on TV (Post) (e). Weekend advance,
moved.

   TV-TIPS -- Best viewing bets for Thursday (Times) (e). Sunday
advance, moved.

   Opinion:

   HOUSE-COMMENT -- Rep. Dan Rostenkowski dismissed his first lawyer
last year and retained Robert Bennett -- the same respected criminal
defense attorney who became a household name a few weeks ago when the
president tapped him to defend against Paula Corbin Jones'
sexual-harassment charges; is there a conflict here? 725 words, by
Michael M. Uhlmann (Times special) (k).

   BIMBOS-COMMENT -- Now that Paula Jones has filed her lawsuit
accusing Bill Clinton of sexual harassment, America once again is
tossing around the word ``bimbo,'' using it to describe Jones in a
pejorative way, usually in defense of the president. 900 words, by
Mike Sweeney (Time) (k).

   HEALTHCARE-COMMENT -- WASHINGTON -- What's causing all the turmoil in
the health-care debate are a few key choices; once those choices are
made, the details begin to fall into place. 1,000 words, by E.J.
Dionne Jr. (Post) (k). Moved.

   DEMOCRACY-COMMENT -- Americans are notorious for optimism and lack
of historical consciousness; it is well to remember that elections are
a necessary but not a sufficient condition for democracy, and that
backsliding to authoritarianism can happen in other countries besides
Peru, Haiti and Serbia. 640 words, by Alison Brysk (Times special)
(k).

   SAFRICA-ARMS-COMMENT -- The little-noticed role of South
African-made arms in the catastrophe of Rwanda presents Nelson Mandela
with an early test of his ability to reconcile realism and idealism.
970 words, by Frank Smyth (Post special) (k). Moved.

   RENO -- Conservatieve losers still winners. By Robert Reno (Newsday)
(k).

   POST EDITORIAL (moved), TIMES EDITORIAL, SUN EDITORIAL (all k).

   Financial:

   MARKET-BEAT -- Why bond bulls need to wake up and smell the coffee.
By Tom Petruno (Times) (f).

