<HEADLINE>
 Editors: 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Los Angeles Times-Washington Post News Service advance feature
budget for May 28 and 29. For questions about stories, the editor is
Bob Crowe at (800) 283-NEWS, ext. 77832 or (213) 237-7832.

   Stories marked ``Sunday advance'' are STRICTLY EMBARGOED for use
Sunday and thereafter. Stories marked ``weekend advance'' are STRICTLY
EMBARGOED for use Saturday and thereafter.

   On the tube:

   TV-DURNING -- Actor Charles Durning tucked away his painful D-Day
memories 50 years ago and has rarely unpacked them since; that changes
with appearances on PBS, at the Memorial Day concert, Sunday, The
Discovery Channel's D-Day program Monday and a CBS special about D-Day
Thursday night. 1,250 words, by Patricia Brennan (Post). With
TV-DURNING-BIO (e). Weekend advance, moved Tuesday.

   TV-WATSON -- HOLLYWOOD -- Karen Foster is a conceited, bubble-headed,
fashion-occupied teen; Angela Watson, who plays Karen on ABC's hit
sitcom ``Step by Step,'' hopes that no one thinks she is that
airheaded. 570 words, by N.F. Mendoza (Times) (e). Sunday advance,
moved Monday.

   TV-INDY-UNSER -- After 13 years of retirement from IndyCar racing,
Bobby Unser still enjoys a live show; he'll be in the ABC television
broadcast booth for Sunday's 78th Indianapolis 500. 710 words, by John
Scheibe (Times) (e). Sunday advance, moved Monday.

   TV-CUP -- A prep course for the month-long World Cup soccer
tournament, to be played in the United States for the first time
beginning June 17, is available in a set of three home videos; also
new basketball videos. 400 words, by Martie Zad (Post) (e). Weekend
advance, moved Tuesday.

   TV-CARROLL - Is Lewis Carroll's timeless ``Alice's Adventures in
Wonderland'' simply an innocent children's story? Those who think so
are in for a fascinating glance through the looking glass on The
Learning Channel's ``Great Books'' series. 500 words, by Scott Moore
(Post) (e). Weekend advance, moved Tuesday.

   TV-KIDS -- Things are definitely not better left unsaid: That's the
message of CBS' prime-time special Break the Silence: Kids Against
Child Abuse. 700 words, by N.F. Mendoza (Times) (e). Sunday advance,
moved Monday.

   TV-OLDIES -- Two years after Johnny Carson signed off as host of
NBC's ``The Tonight Show,'' Buena Vista Home Video is releasing a
four-volume collection of his best moments with ``Johnny Carson: His
Favorite Moments From `The Tonight Show.' '' 600 words, by Susan King
(Times). With TV-OLDIES-RERUNS (e). Sunday advance, moved Monday.

   TV-CABLE -- ``Biography,'' one of the more popular weekly shows on
the Arts Entertainment service, will run Monday through Friday
nights; other cable highlights. 700 words, by Martie Zad (Post) (e).
Weekend advance, moved Thursday, May 19.

   TV-PICKS -- Selecting the week's best on TV. Weekend advance, moved
Tuesday.

   TV-TALKBACK -- Answers to reader questions (Times) (e). Sunday
advance, moved Monday.

   TV-TIPS -- Selected television programs for the week (Times) (e).
Sunday advances, moved Monday.

   In the groove:

   RECORD-RACK -- Reviews of recent releases (Times) (e). Sunday
advance, expectable Thursday.

   On the screen:

   MOVIE-GUIDE -- Capsule reviews of recent releases (Times) (e).
Sunday advance, expectable Wednesday.

   OUTTAKES -- A look inside Hollywood and the movies (Times). Sunday
advance, expectable Thursday.

   The arts:

   DEKOONING -- WASHINGTON -- The magnificent retrospective of his
paintings at the National Gallery of Art throws Willem de Kooning's
breathtaking achievement into high relief; more than ever, he is
confirmed as the last great exemplar of a European tradition of modern
art refracted through an American prism. By Christopher Knight (Times)
(e). Sunday advance, expectable Wednesday.

   Between the lines:

   BOOK-BRIEFS -- Short reviews of recently released books (Times) (e).
Sunday advance, expectable Wednesday.

   BEST-SELLERS-WEST -- What's selling in Southern California (Times)
(e). Sunday advance, expectable Wednesday.

   BEST-SELLERS-EAST -- What's hot on the East Coast (Post) (e). Sunday
advance, expectable Friday.

   BEST-SELLERS-NY -- What's selling in New York (Newsday) (e). Sunday
advance, expectable Thursday.

   Real Estate:

   HOT-PROPERTY -- Melissa Gilbert, who co-stars with Cicely Tyson as a
pair of Southern lawyers who champion the underdog in the fall NBC
series ``Sweet Justice,'' has purchased a three-bedroom home in the
San Fernando Valley area of Los Angeles for about $500,000. By Ruth
Ryon (Times) (e). Sunday advance, expectable Thursday.
