<HEADLINE>
 Good afternoon, AM editors. 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Los Angeles Times-Washington Post News Service Budget for
morning papers of Thursday, May 26, 1994. For questions about stories,
the day editor is John Cullicott at (202) 334-7666, and the night
editor is Michael J. Kaeser at (213) 237-7832.

 National:

   GULFWAR -- WASHINGTON -- Pentagon officials testify before Congress
on reports that shipments of biological-warfare materials to Iraq by
U.S. companies may have contributed to health problems experienced by
Gulf war veterans. Developing.

   ROSTY -- WASHINGTON -- Reports that House Ways and Means Chairman Dan
Rostenkowski, D-Ill., may accept a plea bargain and resign shake the
House and set off some frantic maneuvering. Developing.

   CLINTON -- ANNAPOLIS, Md. -- President Clinton, delivering the
commencement address at the Naval Academy at Annapolis, uses the
occasion to defend his foreign policy in general and his Bosnia policy
in particular. Developing.

   HEALTH -- WASHINGTON -- President Clinton goes to Capitol Hill to
schmooze Democrats on health care as the see-saw battle to get
something passed before the November elections continues. Developing.

   BLACKHOLE -- Astronomers using the Hubble Space Telescope have found
the strongest evidence yet of a black hole, a massive one in the
center of the M87 galaxy 50 million light years away. Developing.

   ELECTION -- WASHINGTON -- Democrats are shaken for the loss of a
congressional seat in Kentucky and worry about the impact on
November's election. Developing, by Dan Balz and Thomas B. Edsall
(Post).

   PRIZE -- LOS ANGELES -- When James Beltran picked up an instant game
ticket worth $1 million, he thought he had it made; but in twists and
turns worthy of an O. Henry story, it has brought him was a host of
troubles. 1,000 words, by Richard Lee Colvin (Times). Moved.

   PRESSER -- CLEVELAND -- A dispute over the $4.2 million estate of the
late Teamsters Union President Jackie Presser has surfaced in court,
and fifth wife Cynthia Presser has admitted violating her duties as
its executor. 850 words, by Robert L. Jackson (Times). Moved.

 International:

   NATO -- BRUSSELS, Belgium -- Russia, moving beyond its latest
decision to join the Partnership for Peace program, proposes beginning
broad talks with NATO on a wide range of issues from nuclear
proliferation to the environment. Developing.

   NATO-MEET -- BRUSSELS, Belgium -- As NATO leaders and their former
Warsaw Pact adversaries gather for the first meeting of the
Partnership for Peace, seasoned diplomats and military officers are
overcome by a sense of witnessing history. Developing, by Art Pine
(Times).

   CHINA-POLICY -- WASHINGTON -- President Clinton meets with national
security advisers and other foreign policy experts as he prepares to
make a final decision on China's trade status; the announcement is
expected Thursday. Developing.

   RWANDA -- NAIROBI, Kenya -- Rwanda's battered army exchanges heavy
mortar fire with rebel guerrillas who have captured a strategic
government position; the fighting again prevents relief supplies from
being flown into Kigali. Developing, by David Lamb (Times).

   RWANDA-NATIONS -- UNITED NATIONS -- U.N. Secretary-General Boutros
Boutros-Ghali, bristling with anger and frustration, blames the
international community for talking but doing little else to stop the
genocide that has swept Rwanda since April. Developing.

   BOSNIA-NIGHTMARE -- SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina -- Western nations'
threats to pull U.N. troops out of Bosnia stir fears of devastating
consequences; a pullout could be lopsided and may guarantee a widening
of the war. 1,275 words, by Carol J. Williams (Times). Moved.

   MACEDONIA -- SKOPJE, Macedonia -- To hear Macedonians talk on the
streets of their capital, the only ones suffering from the blockade
Greece has placed on this landlocked former Yugoslav republic are the
Greeks themselves. 850 words, by Steve Vogel (Post special). Moved.

 Financial:

   NASDAQ -- NEW YORK -- A study by two business school professors
concludes that NASDAQ trading appears rigged to the detriment of
customers; the study, to appear in the Journal of Finance, finds
traders collude on price spreads. Developing, by Scot J. Paltrow
(Times).

   DERIVATIVES -- WASHINGTON -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan,
Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman Arthur Levitt and
Comptroller of the Currency Eugene Ludwig testify before a House
subcommittee on derivatives. Developing, by Brett D. Fromson (Post).

   NAFTA -- Unlike the tame diplomacy that characterized past meetings,
this year's Border Governors Conference in Phoenix, the first since
the North American Free Trade Agreement went into law Jan. 1, will
focus on jobs and federal aid. Developing, by Chris Kraul (Times).

   COFFEE -- Coffee prices worldwide are surging to five-year highs, as
low crop yields and a producers' pact shrink supplies while investment
funds boost their buying of the commodity; analysts say there is no
end in sight to the rally. Developing, by Donald Woutat (Times).

   PHONESEX -- HAGERSTOWN, Md. -- John Rebarick says he had no idea what
or where Sao Tome was until he got the most expensive geography lesson
of his life -- $3,500 in calls on a sex line patronized by his
roommate's girlfriend. 925 words, by Michael Dresser (Sun). Moved.

