<HEADLINE>
bc-times-front
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
 Editors:

   Here is an early look at the stories the Los Angeles Times is
considering for its first-edition Page 1 for Thursday:

   CLINTON-TIMES -- ANNAPOLIS, Md. -- President Clinton uses
commencement at the U.S. Naval Academy as a platform for a sharp
counterattack against critics of his Bosnia policy, accusing the
critics -- including many leaders of his own party -- of advancing
``simplistic ideas that sound good on bumper stickers but that would
have tragic consequences.'' In particular, Clinton denounces proposals
that the United States unilaterally violate the U.N. embargo against
arms shipments to Bosnia, proposals that leading Democrats have
endorsed and that enjoy support in Congress. By David Lauder.

   CHINA-POLICY -- WASHINGTON -- President Clinton prepares to make a
final decision on China's trade benefits as the White House struggles
to get the crucial support of Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell,
the architect of the policy of linking trade to human rights. The
administration is expected to announce its decision as early as
Thursday but it wants if possible to avoid the embarrassment of a
split with Mitchell. Over the past few days, administration officials
have decided to extend China's most-favored-nation trade benefits,
while raising tariffs on weapons made by China's People's Liberation
Army for sale in the United States. By Jim Mann.

   ROSTY-TIMES -- WASHINGTON -- Like a bizarre scene from the old ``Get
Smart'' comedy show, an odd ``cone of decorum'' has descended over the
House as it confronts the apparently imminent departure of Rep. Dan
Rostenkowski -- very likely to prison on a plea bargain to corruption
charges -- as chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee. The
powerful Illinois Democrat, an unparalleled master of arm-twisting and
deal-cutting, is considered critical to the fate of the Clinton
administration's health care reform and the Democrats' overall record
of accomplishment. Members of Congress wonder and worry about who will
succeed him -- and the implications for themselves and President
Clinton -- yet congressional decorum prevents anyone from talking
openly about it. By Karen Tumulty and Ronald J. Ostrow.

   BBN-STRAWBERRY -- LOS ANGELES -- Troubled Dodger outfielder Darryl
Strawberry is placed on waivers for the purpose of giving him his
unconditional release. The Dodgers say they reached a monentary
settlement with Strawberry, who admitted the day before the season
began that he had a substance abuse problem. He entered a treatment
program a short time later. By Maryann Hudson. (Will move on
ALL-SPORTS! service).

   TOBACCO -- Documents leaked from the files of Brown Williamson
Tobacco Co., the No. 3 U.S. cigarette company, are likely to be at the
focus of hearing Thursday by a House Health and Environment
subcommittee headed by Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., a leading
congressional tobacco foe. By Myron Levin.

   For questions, the night editor is Michael J. Kaeser, (800)
283-NEWS, ext. 77832 or (213) 237-7832.
</TEXT>
