<HEADLINE>
 Good morning, PM editors.
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Los Angeles Times-Washington Post News Service budget for
afternoon papers of Thursday, May 26, 1994. For questions about
stories, the PM editor is Stan Roberts in Los Angeles at (800)
283-NEWS, ext. 77832 or (213) 237-7832.

 National:

   CLINTON-ASSESS -- WASHINGTON -- Bill Clinton, who has staked his
presidency on achieving bold domestic policy goals, appears to be
jeopardizing his political future with his handling of U.S. foreign
policy; his poll ratings are wilting, Republicans are pounding him and
discontent is spreading on Capitol Hill. 1,200 words, by Robert Shogan
(Times). New.

   CLINTON-TIMES -- WASHINGTON -- President Clinton uses commencement at
the U.S. Naval Academy as a platform for a counterattack on his Bosnia
policy, denouncing proposals that the U.S. unilaterally violate the
U.N. embargo against arms shipments to the warring parties. 750 words,
by David Lauter (Times). With CLINTON-POST, CLINTON-NDY and
CLINTON-SUN, all moved.

   WELFARE -- WASHINGTON -- Ending months of intense debate within the
administration, President Clinton will propose making it easier for
states to deny additional benefits to women who have children while
already on welfare, senior administration officials say. 1,200 words,
by Ronald Brownstein (Times). Moved.

   ROSTY-TIMES -- WASHINGTON -- An uncommon code of silence envelops the
House as it confronts the strong possibility that Rep. Dan
Rostenkowski, D-Ill., will step down as chairman of the House Ways and
Means Committee as part of a plea bargain. 900 words, by Ronald J.
Ostrow and Karen Tumulty (Times). With ROSTY-POST and ROSTY-SUN, all
moved.

   HEALTH-INSURE -- WASHINGTON -- The percentage of Americans with
employer-paid medical insurance has dropped sharply in 10 years and
the trend is accelerating, the Clinton administration says, as it
released Census Bureau data sure to fuel the health care reform
debate. 570 words, by Edwin Chen (Times). Moved.

   HEALTH-TIMES -- WASHINGTON -- President Clinton makes the rounds of
Capitol Hill to promote his health care agenda, offering a spoonful of
conciliatory honey to Republican senators whose support he hopes to
win. 550 words, by Karen Tumulty (Times). With HEALTH-POST and
HEALTH-NDY, all moved.

   TOBACCO -- Cigarette company lawyers for years ran a ``special
projects'' division within the putatively independent Council for
Tobacco Research, steering grants to favored scientists whose research
might be used to defend the industry from legal attack, internal
documents show. 1,060 words, by Myron Levin (Times). Moved.

   ELECTION-TIMES -- WASHINGTON -- Democratic National Chairman David
Wilhelm denounces Democratic candidates, including the loser in this
week's special House election in Kentucky, for not running on
President Clinton's record. 600 words, by Robert Shogan (Times). With
ELECTION-POST, both moved.

   SOLZHENITSYN -- CAVENDISH, Vt. -- After 18 years of exile in the
wooded hills of small-town Vermont, the great Russian writer and Nobel
Prize winner Alexander Solzhenitsyn leaves much as he arrived -- 
quietly and nearly alone. 700 words, by Christopher B. Daly (Post).
Moved.

   GULFWAR-TIMES -- WASHINGTON -- A Senate report says Pentagon
officials have been concealing or ignoring evidence that tens of
thousands of U.S. Persian Gulf War veterans were exposed to Iraqi
chemical and biological weapons during the conflict. 760 words, by
Jeff Leeds, (Times) . With GULFWAR-POST and GULFWAR-NDY, all moved.

 International:

   RWANDA-NATIONS-TIMES -- UNITED NATIONS -- Secretary-general Boutros
Boutros-Ghali, bristling with anger and frustration, derides the
international community for talking but doing little else to stop
genocide in Rwanda. 570 words, by Stanley Meisler (Times). With
RWANDA-NATIONS-POST and RWANDA, all moved.

   HAITI-REFUGEES -- WASHINGTON -- In seeking to implement quickly a new
program for processing Haitian boat people and answer its critics, the
Clinton administration is relying on a set of calculations that
involve a peculiar mix of mathematics and morality. 950 words, by
Roberto Suro (Post). Moved.

   BOSNIA-FRANCE -- BONN, Germany -- French President Francois
Mitterrand, defending his apparent failure to investigate
concentration camps in Bosnia after a top-level appeal, says that
France did more and acted faster than any other country. 1,050 words,
by Roy Gutman (Newsday). Moved.

   MIDEAST-POLICE -- JERICHO, West Bank -- The quick appearance of the
Palestinian secret police in this West Bank town rings -- for some -- an
ominous note among the celebrations over Israeli withdrawal. 1,000
words, by Doug Struck (Sun). New. With MIDEAST-POLICY, moved.

   RUSSIA-CITY -- VLADIVOSTOK, Russia -- Vladivostok is like a carnival
mirror's distorted image of Russia itself: distended in its
lawlessness, misery and disorientation, but also in its gaudy new
wealth and commercial promise. 1,060 words, by Lee Hockstader (Post).
New.

   CHINA-POLICY-TIMES -- WASHINGTON -- President Clinton is expected to
announce Thursday that he will renew China's trade privileges, but he
may impose extremely limited sanctions on Chinese-made guns and
ammunition, according to sources who were briefed on the White House
decision. 890 words, by Jim Mann (Times). With CHINA-POLICY-POST, both
moved.

