<DOC id="LTW_ENG_19940526.0030" type="story" >
<HEADLINE>
 Letting the Sun Cool It 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
How do you keep ice cream from melting in the sun?
</P>
<P>
Let the sun cool it.
</P>
<P>
The first solar-powered refrigerated vending cart made its debut
this month in Washington. Even when the outdoor temperature pushes 90
degrees, the four 30-watt solar panels spread out like an umbrella
above the vendor's head will generate enough electricity to maintain
approximately 500 popsicles at near zero degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
Even under overcast skies, the deep cycle-type battery keeps the
compressor going. Super-efficient insulation keeps the cold in,
eliminating the need to stock the cart with 25 to 30 pounds of dry ice
daily, about $10 worth.
</P>
<P>
A solar system for a pushcart was conceived by New York industrial
designer Amelia Amon and engineered by Jody Solell and Carmela Knepler
of Solar Electrics in Fairfax, Va. Solarex of Frederick, Md., made the
lightweight panels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
