   Editors, Managing editors:

   The following features on the 50th anniversary of the D-Day
invasion of Europe are tentatively scheduled to move before the June 6
anniversary date. In addition, news stories and event-related features
will move as they develop.

   DDAY-INVASION -- A primer on D-day: what happened, who took part,
why it was so important. 2,000 words, by Rick Atkinson (Post) (i).
Advance for Sunday, May 29; expectable late in week of May 23.

   DDAY-RECON -- Dozens of veterans -- American, British, French,
Canadian and German -- recall what happened on D-Day and what it meant
for World War II; chapters dealing with the preparations, the bombing,
the shelling, the landings in various sectors and the German response.
8,000 words, by Richard E. Meyer (Times) (i). Tentatively five parts.
Expectable the week of May 30 for immediate use.

   DDAY-REAGAN -- The former president reminisces about the Normany
invasion and about his trip to the D-Day anniversary celebrations 10
years ago. 1,000 words, by Ronald Reagan (Post special) (k). Advance
for Sunday, June 5; expectable week of May 30.

   DDAY-GI -- Soldier Edward Regan stepped off his landing craft and
nearly drowned; as he struggled forward and lay exhausted off the
beach he was immortalized by photographer Robert Capa. 500 words, by
James Kindall (Newsday) (i). Expectable Wednesday, June 1, for
immediate use.

   DDAY-PLANS -- How the invasion was planned, the secrecy, deception.
1,500 words, by Ken Ringle (Post) (i). Expectable week of May 30 for
immediate use.

   DDAY-GAMBLE -- The gamble and the extraordinary logistical effort to
build a huge and complex harbor in secret, float it across the channel
and surprise the Germans. By Ken Ringle (Post) (i). Expectable week of
May 30 for immediate use.

   DDAY-RUSE -- The Germans figured only one spot was feasible for an
Allied crossing of the English Channel, the Pas de Calais; it was
completely logical, but completely wrong. 800 words, by David Kahn
(Newsday) (i). Expectable Wednesday, June 1, for immediate use.

   DDAY-WHATIF -- What would have happened if the Normandy invasion had
failed? Would the Allies have sued for peace and Europe been dominated
by the Nazis, or would there simply have been another and bloodier
attempt? 1,000 words, by William McTernan (Newsday) (i). Expectable
Wednesday, June 1, for immediate use.

   DDAY-POLICY -- For better or worse, the Normandy invasion was one of
a series of events that propelled America past the point of no return
on the road toward a permanent global role; only the end of communism,
a deepening budgetary crisis and a string of pressing domestic
problems have led the United States to begin unwinding its presence in
Europe. 2,500 words, by Tyler Marshall (Times) (i). Expectable
Tuesday, May 31, for immediate use.

   DDAY-BRITAIN -- LONDON -- How the British view the invasion and its
aftermath. By Steve Coll (Post) (i).

   DDAY-GERMANS -- BERLIN -- How the Germans are reacting to still
another World War II anniversary. By Rick Atkinson (Post) (i).

   DDAY-BEDFORD -- BEDFORD, Va. -- Long gone are the boys of Bedford,
gone these 50 years, lost in the roiling English Channel and on the
sands of Omaha Beach; the 19 sons of Bedford killed on D-Day, the
largest proportion of casualties for any community in the nation, lie
under great oak trees at the town cemetery. 1,300 words, by Richard A.
Serrano (Times) (a). Expectable the week of May 30, for immediate use.

