<HEADLINE>
 Good afternoon, AM editors. 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Los Angeles Times-Washington Post News Service Budget for
morning papers of Friday, May 27, 1994. For questions about stories,
the day editor is John Cullicott at (202) 334-7666, and the night
editor is Michael J. Kaeser at (213) 237-7832.

 National:

   ABORTION -- WASHINGTON -- President Clinton signs legislation
guaranteeing access to abortion clinics; protests erupt and an
anti-abortion group immediately files suit challenging the action,
setting up a key court test on the volatile issue. Developing.

   ABORTION-CALIF -- SAN FRANCISCO -- The California Supreme Court is
expected to rule on a case that would set limits on anti-abortion
protests outside abortion clinics. Developing, by Maura Dolan (Times).

   WELFARE -- WASHINGTON -- The Clinton administration has made it
easier for states to impose benefits restrictions on welfare
recipients. Developing, by William Claiborne (Post).

   WHITEWATER -- WASHINGTON -- The special prosecutor goes to Capitol
Hill to brief congressional leaders. Developing.

   CLINTON-ASSESS -- WASHINGTON -- Bill Clinton, who staked his
presidency on achieving bold domestic policy goals, may be
jeopardizing his political future with his handling of U.S. foreign
policy, opinion polls show. 1,200 words, by Robert Shogan (Times).
Moved.

   CREATURE -- The remains of a 6-foot-long animal that looks like a
basic, back-yard pinchbug have been put together in China, according
to scientists who note that it predates dinosaurs by hundreds of
millions of years. Developing, by Robert Cooke (Newsday).

 International:

   CHINA-POLICY -- WASHINGTON -- President Clinton is reportedly close
to making an announcement on China's trade privileges, a decision that
is sure to be a controversial balancing act between human rights
progress and international trade benefits. Developing.

   JAPAN -- TOKYO -- Emperor Akihito and Empress Michiko will pay
respects to American war dead at Arlington National Cemetery and in
Honolulu -- but not at Pearl Harbor -- during a tour of the United
States beginning June 10, Japan announces. Developing, by Sam Jameson
(Times).

   HAITI-POLICY -- WASHINGTON -- The United States plans to bolster
enforcement of the Haiti embargo. Developing, by Thomas W. Lippman
(Post).

   MEXICO -- MEXICO CITY -- Mexico denies it is persecuting the family
of Mario Aburto Martinez, the accused assassin of presidential
candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio, after family members flee Mexico and
request U.S. political asylum. Developing, by Juanita Darling (Times).

   PHIL -- MANILA, Philippines -- Philippine authorities arrest the
communist leader of an urban assassination squad. Developing, by
William Branigin (Post).

   RUSSIA -- BALASHIKHA, Russia -- Named after feared secret police
chief Felix Dzerzhinsky, the Dzerzhinsky Division did the Kremlin's
dirty work; in a bizarre display of Western-style public relations,
its base is opened to the public. Developing.

   RUSSIA-CITY -- VLADIVOSTOK, Russia -- Vladivostok is like a carnival
mirror's distorted image of Russia: distended in its lawlessness,
misery and disorientation, but also in its gaudy wealth and commercial
promise. 1,060 words, by Lee Hockstader (Post). Moved.

   SAFRICA -- JOHANNESBURG, South Africa -- With U.N. sanctions on South
African arms exports lifted, President Nelson Mandela's new government
gives a green light to the industry's desire to increase sales to
foreign countries. Developing, by Paul Taylor (Post).

   ITALY -- ROME -- In an interview, Italy's new prime minister, Silvio
Berlusconi, outlines the direction of his conservative government.
Developing, by William Drozdiak (Post).

   MIDEAST-POLICE -- JERICHO, West Bank -- The quick appearance of
Palestinian secret police in this West Bank town rings -- for some -- an
ominous note among the celebrations over Israeli withdrawal. 1,000
words, by Doug Struck (Sun). Moved.

   DDAY-EVENTS -- POOLE, England -- As the 50th anniversary of D-day
looms, southern England braces for a flood of outsiders; counting on
the nostalgia boom, tourism officials expect to lure about 350,000
visitors. 1,140 words, by William Tuohy (Times). Moved.

 Financial:

   ECONOMY -- WASHINGTON -- Recent economic statistics indicate that the
economy has moderated in the current quarter. Developing, by John M.
Berry (Post).

   WORLDCUP-MERCHANDISE -- NEW YORK -- An underground economy of World
Cup merchandise, stretching from leather factories in Pakistan to
print shops and retail stores in New York City, cuts into profits of
more than 300 companies. 900 words by Mitch Gelman (Newsday). Moved.

