<HEADLINE>
 Good afternoon, AM editors. 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Los Angeles Times-Washington Post News Service Budget for
morning papers of Saturday, May 28, 1994. For questions about stories,
the day editor is John Cullicott at (202) 334-7666, and the night
editor is Michael J. Kaeser at (213) 237-7832.

 International:

   CHINA -- BEIJING -- China reacts with restrained satisfaction to
President Clinton's announcement that the United States is renewing
its favorable trade terms, despite the Beijing government's lack of
progress on human rights. Developing.

   CHINA-ASSESS -- BEIJING -- China's success in overcoming human rights
opposition to win renewal of trade privileges boils down to a simple
truth: China understands the U.S. system better than the Americans
understand China's. Developing, by Rone Tempest (Times).

   VATICAN -- The Vatican unveils its new 688-page English-language
catechism, the first compendium of Roman Catholic teaching in 400
years. Developing.

   KOREA -- WASHINGTON -- After analyzing an international inspection
team's findings, the Clinton administration finds that North Korea has
not been diverting fuel from its primary atomic reactor to make
nuclear weapons. Developing, by Art Pine (Times).

   RUSSIA -- VLADIVOSTOCK, Russia -- Writer Alexander I. Solzhenitsyn
ends his 20-year exile with an appeal to people across Russia to
direct their country's post-Communist rebirth by seizing more
initiative from their rulers. Developing.

   ISRAEL -- JERUSALEM -- Former Israeli defense minister Ariel Sharon
launches a campaign to oust Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin in 1996; but
Sharon's announcement is more a challenge to his Likud Party rival,
Benjamin Netanyahu. Developing.

   JAPAN -- TOKYO -- As the emperor prepares for a 16-day U.S. tour, a
group of American journalists is invited for tea; the scene.
Developing, by T.R. Reid (Post).

   QUEBEC -- TORONTO -- Canada is being dragged reluctantly into a
confrontation over the future of French-speaking Quebec; political
leaders have squabbled over the revived prospect of Quebec
independence. 710 words, by Craig Turner (Times). Moved.

   NICARAGUA-ORTEGA -- MANAGUA, Nicaragua -- President Violeta Barrios
de Chamorro, working to bring the army under civilian control, looks
forward to next year when Gen. Humberto Ortega, the powerful army
chief, steps down. 590 words, by Tracy Wilkinson (Times). Moved.

   GERMANS -- FRANKFURT, Germany -- To stay or leave, integrate or
isolate; these questions plague Holocaust survivors, who settled in
Germany after the Nazi extermination of 6 million Jews, and weigh on
their children and grandchildren. 1,330 words, by Marjorie Miller
(Times). Moved.

 National:

   FED -- WASHINGTON -- Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan
defends the recent runup in interest rates, telling a congressional
committee that putting the brakes on a rapidly expanding economy now
would prevent an economic slowdown. Developing.

   DRUGS -- WASHINGTON -- A bitter interagency squabble has erupted
between the Pentagon and the State Department over drug enforcement in
South America. Developing, by Barton Gellman (Post).

   SMOKING -- MIAMI -- Florida's decision to authorize class-action
lawsuits against tobacco companies for diseases associated with
smoking follows similar actions by other states. Developing, by
William Booth (Post).

 Financial:

   NAFTA -- PHOENIX -- U.S. officials tell border states and cities they
will have to come up with innovative ways, such as tolls and fees, to
pay for border infrastructure if they are to realize benefits of jobs
and business growth. Developing, by Chris Kraul (Times).

