<HEADLINE>
bc-times-front
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
 Editors:

   Here is an early look at the stories the Los Angeles Times is
considering for its first-edition Page 1 for Saturday:

   RUSSIA-TIMES -- VLADIVOSTOK, Russia -- Solemn and prophetic,
Alexander I. Solzhenitsyn ends his 20-year exile in the United States
with an appeal to people across Russia to direct their troubled
country's post-Communist rebirth by seizing more initiative from their
rulers in Moscow. Even though the country's greatest living author has
forsworn any ambition to elective or appointed office, his voice could
become a rallying cry for regional and local leaders seeking to wrest
more autonomy from the central government of President Boris N.
Yeltsin. By Richard Boudreaux.

   CHINA-ASSESS -- BEIJING -- In the end, China's success in overcoming
human rights opposition to win renewal of trade privileges from the
United States boils down to one simple truth: The Chinese regime
demonstrated a much better understanding of the American political
system than the Clinton administration did of the Chinese system. The
key to the Chinese strategy was to divert attention from human rights
issues to the blinding lights of China's booming economy and huge
potential market. By Rone Tempest.

   TICKETS -- LOS ANGELES -- The U.S. Justice Department has begun an
antitrust investigation of Los Angeles-based Ticketmaster after a top
rock band accused the giant ticket agency of organizing a boycott by
promoters of a low-cost concert tour. The probe began after lawyers
for the Seattle rock group Pearl Jam complained on May 6 to the
department's antitrust division in Washington. The band accused
Ticketmaster, the world's largest ticket agency, of exercising a
monopoly over ticket distribution and using that influence to keep
promoters from booking Pearl Jam's tour this summer. By Chuck Philips.

   SPEAK -- LONG BEACH, Calif. -- They wanted a role model, a teacher, a
motivator of young people to issue the final challenge to the Class of
'94. So administrators at Long Beach State's College of the Arts were
gleeful when this year's commencement speaker took the podium, an
unlikely sight in black academic robes and mortar board: Tommy
Lasorda. In what may have been the only graduation exercise covered by
ESPN, the Dodgers manager and diet-drink pitchman told the crowd of
aspiring Pacinos, Baryshnikovs and Van Cliburns what it takes for them
to succeed in life. Lasorda's appearance shows how far colleges will
go to entertain and inspire their charges before sending them off into
the cruel world. The reason: With more than 3,500 schools all looking
for keynote speakers at the same time of the year, the competition
means administrators must stalk eye-catching names for months, put the
grip on through influential alums or else settle for muffled
disappointment. By Ralph Frammolino.

   For questions, the night editor is Michael J. Kaeser, (800)
283-NEWS, ext. 77832 or (213) 237-7832.
</TEXT>
