<HEADLINE>
 Good morning, PM editors.
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Los Angeles Times-Washington Post News Service budget for
afternoon papers of Saturday, May 28, 1994. All stories have moved.

 National:

   CLINTON -- WASHINGTON -- President Clinton, concerned by a loss of
public confidence in his leadership on foreign policy, says that he
has consulted widely but has rejected recommendations that he replace
Secretary of State Warren Christopher and White House national
security adviser Anthony Lake. 900 words, by Jack Nelson and Doyle
McManus (Times).

   CLINTON-AIDE-TIMES -- Thirteen top White House officials agree to
help David Watkins pick up the tab for his use of a military
helicopter; the agreement comes as White House officials disclose that
a second Marine helicopter also had gone on the outing. 860 words, by
Paul Richter (Times). With CLINTON-AIDE-NDY and CLINTON-AIDE-POST.

   FED-TIMES -- WASHINGTON -- Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan
Greenspan mounts his first public defense of the Fed's repeated
interest rate increases this year, telling a skeptical Congress that
the central bank had no alternative but to hike rates to reduce the
threat of inflation. 680 words, by James Risen (Times). With FED-POST.

   TICKETS (1stld) -- In a memorandum to the U.S. Justice Department,
the rock band Pearl Jam has complained that Los Angeles-based
Ticketmaster successfully pressured promoters to boycott the band's
low-cost concert tour this summer. 640 words, by Chuck Philips (Times
special).

   AMES -- WASHINGTON -- The House and Senate intelligence committees
have been asked by Justice Department officials to delay their
possible questioning of confessed-spy Aldrich H. Ames until the FBI
and CIA have finished debriefing him, according to administration and
congressional sources. 500 words, by Walter Pincus (Post).

   AIR -- SAN FRANCISCO -- A 10-year study of smog in national parks has
found that air quality is improving in Western states but continuing
to deteriorate in the East despite tougher laws aimed at halting air
pollution. 625 words, by Richard C. Paddock (Times).

   SPEAK -- LONG BEACH, Calif. -- With more than 3,500 schools hunting
graduation speakers this year, administrators must stalk eye-catching
names for months and put the grip on influential alums to avoid
stifled yawns and even embarrassment at commencement time. 1,300
words, by Ralph Frammolino (Times).

 International:

   CHINA-ASSESS -- BEIJING -- China's success in winning renewal of
trade privileges from the United States occurred because it
demonstrated a better understanding of the American political system
than the Clinton administration did of the Chinese system. 1,335
words, by Rone Tempest (Times).

   CHINA-POLICY -- WASHINGTON -- The end game between the United States
and China, which climaxed Thursday with President Clinton's decision
to extend China's trading privileges, began at Richard M. Nixon's
funeral in late April when top administration officials organized a
last-ditch effort to persuade China to improve its human rights
record. 1,290 words, by Daniel Williams and Ann Devroy (Post).

   BOSNIA -- TRAVNIK, Bosnia-Herzegovina -- There is a yawning gap in
understanding between officers of the U.N. operation here and the
military men of the warring Bosnian factions that have brought Europe
its bloodiest conflict since World War II; denizens of different
cultures and different worlds, they can neither shake hands nor salute
when they meet. 980 words, by John Pomfret (Post).

 Financial:

   OIL -- Five key U.S. maritime unions formally agree to support
lifting a federal ban on the export of Alaskan crude oil, in a deal
worked out with British Petroleum Co. 420 words, by Michael Parrish
(Times).
