<HEADLINE>
 Good afternoon, AM editors. 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Los Angeles Times-Washington Post News Service Budget for
morning papers of Sunday, May 29, 1994. For questions about stories,
the day editor is Paul Freedman at (202) 334-7666, and the night
editor is Larry Kusnitt at (213) 237-7832.

 National:

   ROSTY -- WASHINGTON -- Saying he plans to fight charges he misused
government money, embattled House Ways and Means Committee Chairman
Rep. Dan Rostenkowski rejects a plea-bargain offer. Developing.

   HEALTH-PLANS -- WASHINGTON -- Critics complain President Clinton's
health-reform plan would not do enough to preserve choice of doctors;
in fact, Clinton's plan, more than any other politically viable reform
proposal, would increase choice of doctors for most patients; but
there's a catch. 1,270 words, by Edwin Chen (Times). Moved.

   DDAY-INVASION -- A primer on D-day: what happened, who took part,
why it was so important. 3,500 words, by Rick Atkinson (Post). With
DDAY-INVASION-DECEPTION, both Sunday advances, moved Friday.

   DDAY-BEDFORD -- BEDFORD, Va. -- These were the young men who would
never marry their sweethearts or dazzle the younger boys with stories
of heroism on D-day, June 6, 1944; these 19 sons of Bedford killed on
D-day alone were the largest proportion of casualties for any
community in the nation. 1,430 words, by Richard A. Serrano (Times).
Moved.

   CLINTON-POLICY -- WASHINGTON -- Meet Bill Clinton, America's top
salesman; Clinton's decision to renew most-favored-nation status for
China once again underscores how much the central focus of this
administration is catering to big business. Developing, by Glenn
Kessler (Newsday).

   CLINTON-CRITICS -- WASHINGTON -- A cottage industry called
``Clinton-bashing'' has grown so big and raucous that even some
conservatives, including syndicated columnist Cal Thomas, think it is
becoming counterproductive and taking conservatives away from
challenging President Clinton on policy. Developing, by Martin
Kasindorf (Newsday).

   KENNEDY -- WASHINGTON -- These are glorious days for Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, America's aging political prince; after three tumultuous
decades of high drama and low moments, Kennedy is playing a pivotal
role in what could be the crowning achievement of his career:
enactment of national health-care legislation. 950 words, by Karen
Hosler (Sun). Moved.

   DONATE -- LOS ANGELES -- The latest cause gaining appeal in Los
Angeles is not AIDS or the homeless or even the rain forest -- it's the
Los Angeles Police Department; with such recent offerings as cash,
computers, cameras, furniture -- even a motor home -- donations to the
LAPD have surpassed the tally for all of 1993. 890 words, by Hugo
Martin (Times). Moved.

   SWAT -- LOS ANGELES -- The Los Angeles Police Department is trying to
adopt a more community-oriented style that bears little resemblance to
the work its SWAT officers perform; that leaves SWAT at a telling
juncture in its history, caught between the LAPD that gave birth to it
and the one that houses it today. 1,275 words, by Jim Newton (Times).
Moved.

 International:

   RUSSIA -- VLADIVOSTOK, Russia -- What is Alexander I. Solzhenitsyn's
identity as he comes home from 20 years of exile to help post-Soviet
Russia find its own? can the Nobel laureate depend for some measure of
special protection on a government he criticizes so fiercely?
Developing.

   BOSNIA-ANALYSIS -- SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina -- There is mounting
evidence that the U.N. mission in Bosnia has neither the will nor the
political backing to use force against transgressors; and Bosnian
officials resent the attitude that they should accept defeat by a
force repeatedly castigated by the United Nations as the war's
instigator. 900 words, by Carol J. Williams (Times).

   BOSNIA-ISLAM -- SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina -- Amid the hardships of
war and the Christian world's growing indifference to the plight of
Bosnian Muslims, the desire to express a faith that was repressed here
for most of this century is becoming more common. 1,330 words, by
Carol J. Williams (Times).

   ISRAEL-TAP -- JERUSALEM -- No one knows why the cellular phones of
231 Israelis -- many politically prominent, some financially powerful
but a few relatively obscure -- were methodically tapped for eight
months by two Tel Aviv private investigators. 550 words, by Michael
Parks (Times). Moved.

   CHINA-SHOOT -- BEIJING -- The China North International Shooting
Range offers the chance to fire anything from a small pistol to an
anti-aircraft machine gun; such ranges were ordered closed by China's
central government last year -- but this one has remained open because
it also functions as a showcase of Norinco's smaller arms to potential
bulk buyers from abroad. 1,060 words, by Robert Benjamin (Sun). Moved.

   ASIA -- More and more, the economically booming nations of Asia are
flexing their political muscle in disputes with the United States and
the West, especially on such sensitive issues as human rights, freedom
of expression and labor rights. 1,400 words, by Charles P. Wallace.
(Times). Moved.

   BRITAIN-FLOWERS -- LONDON -- Since 1888, the Chelsea Flower Show has
been the most genteel of British institutions; but this year a scandal
has rocked the flower show and dealt a blow to a great British
tradition: It has been revealed that many of the exhibitors have shown
flower displays not from their own gardens. 600 words, by William
Tuohy (Times). Moved.

   Commentary:

   DDAY-ITALY-COMMENT -- A week from Monday, all eyes will be on
Normandy for 50th anniversary of one of history's great moments,
D-Day; here's a question: What important 50th anniversary will occur
two days earlier, on June 4? it's the Allied liberation of Rome, the
first enemy capital to fall; Italy, the forgotten front. 1,300 words,
by Paul S. Green (Post special). Sunday advance, moved Friday.
