 Editors:
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
   Los Angeles Times first-edition Page 1 for Monday, May 30, 1994:

   Top of page:

   Col 1: The Los Angeles Coliseum, home of touchdowns, car races and
political conventions, was knocked on its back by the Jan. 17 quake.
Now the task of rebuilding it has become a metaphor of renewal, even
self-love.

   Cols 2-5: Art of local Memorial Day festivities.

   Col 6: After the breakdown of talks between a United Nations team
and North Korea, U.S. lawmakers issue new warnings about the
consequences if North Korea does not agree to international monitoring
to prevent development of a nuclear weapons program. (KOREA-POLICY,
moved.)

   Above fold:

   Col 2: In a spree of brazen invasion-style heists, suspected Los
Angeles gang members have stormed into casinos in Las Vegas, rifled
through the cashier's cages and made off with tens of thousands of
dollars. Image-conscious proprietors have begin beefing up their
intentionally low-key security measures. (GANGS, moved.)

   Cols 3-4: In contemplating a future not entailing occupation duties
of Gaza and the West Bank, Israel is finally able, in the view of many
of its liberal thinkers, to return to the question, profound and
contentious, of what kind of nation it should be. (ISRAEL-FUTURE,
moved.)

   Col 5: Erich Honecker, the former East German Communist leader who
built the Cold War's most chilling monument, the infamous Berlin Wall,
dies of liver cancer at his home in Santiago, Chile, in exile.
(HONECKER, moved.)

   Below fold:

   Col 4: Just a few years ago, Houston was considered a model for
community policing -- a concept that has caught on in other big cities
looking to rebuild public trust in their police departments. While Los
Angeles is only slowly implementing the program as a result of the
1991 beating of black motorist Rodney King by white police officers,
Houston officials claim to have learned the hard way that the effort
never really paid off. (HOUSTON, moved.)

   Bottom of page:

   Cols 1-2: A $2 billion statewide parks bond measure that has
captured a broad base of support from California nature lovers has
also attracted tens of thousands of dollars in campaign contributions
from landowners who stand to gain if the initiative passes June 7.

   Cols 5-6: Feature on controversy over ethnic play at local arts
school.

