<HEADLINE>
 Good afternoon, AM editors. 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Los Angeles Times-Washington Post News Service Budget for
morning papers of Tuesday, May 31, 1994. For questions about stories,
the day editor is John Cullicott at (202) 334-7666, and the night
editor is Larry Kusnitt at (213) 237-7832.

 International:

   POPE -- VATICAN CITY -- In a stern once-and-for-all veto, Pope John
Paul II reasserts a ban against women priests, ordering Catholics to
end internal debate and obey historic teachings. Developing, by
William D. Montalbano (Times).

   SOMALIA -- NAIROBI, Kenya -- Somalia's feuding factional leaders fail
in an effort to get peace talks started. Developing, by Keith B.
Richburg (Post).

   MIDEAST -- JERUSALEM -- Not even a month old, the Palestinian
Authority is facing a crisis that could bring its collapse -- an acute
shortage of cash; although promised $2.4 billion for economic
development over five years, the new Palestinian administration has
virtually no funds with which to operate. Developing, by Michael Parks
(Times).

   CROATIA -- VIENNA -- Croatia revives a currency used by World War II
fascists, an unhappy emblem for a country trying to make peace with
Bosnian and Serb neighbors. Developing, by John Pomfret (Post).

   INDIA -- NEW DELHI -- Even for India, notorious for heat and dust,
this summer has been a sizzler. How hot has it been? New Delhi sweats
though its hottest afternoon in a half-century, with the mercury
shooting up to 114.8 degrees. Developing, by John-Thor Dalhburg
(Times).

   ALIGN -- CAIRO, Egypt -- The Non-Aligned Movement created by
Yugoslavian leader Josip Tito, Egyptian president Gamal Abdul Nasser
and Indian Prime Minister Jawhar Lal Nehru convenes in Cairo for its
11th Council of Ministers in a dramatically changed world. Developing,
by Kim Murphy (Times).

 National:

   ISLAM -- RIVERSIDE, Calif. -- Authorities here try to sort out motive
for the shooting of former Nation of Islam spokesman Khalid Abdul
Muhammad outside a university auditorium where he had spoken.
Developing.

   ROSTY -- WASHINGTON -- Federal prosecutors are ready to indict Rep.
Dan Rostenkowski, D -- Ill., Tuesday if there is no agreement on a plea
bargain. Developing, by Pierre Thomas (Post).

   SPY -- WASHINGTON -- A key date connected with the actions of former
CIA officer Aldrich H. Ames is in dispute and leaves the possibility
that another double agent remains undiscovered in either U.S. or
British intelligence. 800 words, by Walter Pincus (Post).

   HOUSTON-OBIT -- WASHINGTON -- Paul Green Houston, a longtime
Washington correspondent for the Los Angeles Times and author of its
popular weekly ``Washington Insight'' column, dies after a two-year
battle with colon cancer. Developing (Times).

 Financial:

   JOBS -- WASHINGTON -- A new survey by Manpower Inc. says U.S.
businesses intend to hire more employees this summer than at any time
over the past five years. Developing, by Daniel Southerland (Post).

   BOXOFFICE -- HOLLYWOOD -- The summer movie season kicks off with a
the words ``Yabba-Dabba-Doo!,'' as ``The Flintstones,'' starring John
Goodman as Fred Flintstone, sets a record opening for the Memorial Day
weekend. Developing, by David J. Fox (Times).

