<HEADLINE>
 Good morning, PM editors.
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Los Angeles Times-Washington Post News Service budget for
afternoon papers of Tuesday, May 31, 1994. For questions about
stories, the PM editor is Heather Ann Stewart in Los Angeles at (800)
283-NEWS, ext. 77832 or (213) 237-7832.

 National:

   ROSTY-TIMES (1stld) -- WASHINGTON -- House Ways and Means Committee
Chairman Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., says that he has chosen to fight
charges of fraud and abuse of his public office, rather than making a
deal with federal prosecutors to plead guilty to lesser offenses. 820
words, by Karen Tumulty (Times). Moved.

   ISLAM-TIMES (1stld) -- RIVERSIDE, Calif. -- A former Nation of Islam
minister who clashed with fellow Muslims had a small arsenal nearby
when he allegedly shot black nationalist Khallid Abdul Muhammad and
five other men outside a university auditorium. 890 words, by Carla
Hall and Tom Gorman (Times). With ISLAM-POST, both moved.

   JOBS -- WASHINGTON -- U.S. business executives intend to hire more
employees this summer than at any time over the past five years, says
a new report by the country's largest temporary-help firm. 640 words,
by Daniel Southerland (Post). Moved.

   CHINA-POLICY -- WASHINGTON -- President Clinton, striving to
demonstrate continued American pressure to end Chinese human rights
abuses, outlines a five-point program ``to support forces of
constructive change in China while strengthening the U.S.-China
relationship.'' 630 words, by Robin Wright and Jim Mann (Times).
Moved.

   CLINTON-ANALYSIS-SUN -- WASHINGTON -- President Clinton will depart
on the first of two back-to-back European trips in hopes of reversing
his growing reputation as a weak or indifferent world leader. 1020
words, by Carl M. Cannon (Sun). New.

   CLINTON-ANALYSIS -- WASHINGTON -- The stubbornness of dictatorships
has become one of the Clinton administration's chief foreign-policy
vexations; the recent dismal results of earnest U.S. diplomacy have
not been flattering to America's self-image as a world leader. 1,000
words, by R. Jeffrey Smith (Post). Moved.

   WHITEWATER -- Just when President Bill Clinton thought it was safe
to focus on his health-care agenda, Whitewater is likely to come back
to haunt him again with the start of congressional hearings this
summer. 375 words, by Charles V. Zehren (Newsday). New.

   SUDAN -- WASHINGTON -- Not content with trying to broker peace
between Israel and Syria and head off nuclear confrontation between
India and Pakistan, the Clinton administration is wading into another
seemingly intractable conflict, the civil war in Sudan. 860 words, by
Thomas W. Lippman (Post). New.

   BROWN -- SAN DIEGO -- ``We all know that housework, if done right,
can kill you,'' quips Kathleen Brown, aiming her message as California
gubernatorial candidate at professional women juggling work, families
and careers. 430 words, by Martin Kasindorf (Newsday). New.

 International:

   MIDEAST-JIHAD -- GAZA, Gaza Strip -- Hani Abed, a 31-year-old
university teacher, may be the first secret arrest -- and perhaps first
political arrest -- by the new Palestinian authority in the Gaza Strip.
730 words, by Doug Struck (Sun). New. With MIDEAST-TIMES, MIDEAST-NDY
and MIDEAST-SUN, all moved.

   DDAY-ACTION -- COLLEVILLE SUR MER, France -- Many D-day veterans and
veteran groups have been vising France for pre-anniversary gatherings
over the past few months to avoid the coming crush. 920 words, by
James Kindall (Newsday) . New.

   CROATIA -- VIENNA -- Croatia revives a currency used by World War II
fascists, an unhappy emblem for a country trying to make peace with
Bosnian and Serb neighbors. 540 words, by John Pomfret (Post).

 Financial:

   PARTTIME -- The number of ``involuntary'' part-time employees has
almost tripled since 1970; almost one out of every five employees -- 
more than 21 million -- have part-time jobs, and the trend is emerging
as a hotly contested one in union negotiations. 920 words, by Kenneth
C. Crowe (Newsday). New.

   ADS-WORLDCUP -- World Cup sponsors are gambling $500 million on
advertising rights despite Americans' past indifference to the world's
most popular sport; 19 businesses will spend as much as $20 million
each for sponsorship rights to the soccer championships. which start
next month. 910 words, by Alexander Roy (Newsday). New.

 Spotlight:

   BREYER -- WASHINGTON -- Judge Stephen G. Breyer's strong desire to
use his formidable legal talents to make a practical impact beyond
Ivory Tower theorizing, coupled with a keen appreciation of the
quickest, surest routes toward his own advancement, all but make his
confirmation to the nation's highest court certain. 1,320 words, by
David Lauter (Times). With BREYER-BIO, both new.

