<TEXT>
   The Los Angeles Times-Washington Post News Service feature budget
for Tuesday, May 31, 1994. The feature editor is Bob Crowe in Los
Angeles at (800) 283-NEWS, ext. 77832, or (213) 237-7832. Other key
phone numbers for repeats or general questions, are listed at the
bottom of this advisory.

 Category codes of stories are in parentheses. 

   Travel:

   TRAVEL-WINNIPEG -- Winnipeg may not offer the night life of New York
or the glamour of Paris; but for a low-key, relaxing and safe place to
visit, it is a very pleasant discovery. 1,300 words, by Sandra McKee
(Sun) (t).

   TRAVEL-ECONOMY -- Most cruise lines reward their frequent passengers
with perks like special discounts and private parties, but Cunard is
launching a plan that sounds like a seagoing version of the airline
frequent-flier programs. 700 words, by Barbara Shea (Newsday) (t).

   FEARLESS-TRAVELER -- Tracking tickets to cultural events abroad. By
James Yenckel (Post) (t).

   TOURS CRUISES -- Cooking up a vacation in Italy's lake district. By
Karin Dominello (Times) (t).

   TRAVEL-NOTES -- London larks. By Donna Miskin (Newsday) (t).

   TRAVEL-PLANNER -- Finland packages, culinary journeys, scenic walks.
By Marc Cottone (Newsday) (t).

   WORLDWISE -- What not to do in Singapore; other travel notes. By
Barbara Ann Curcio (Post special) (t).

   Lifestyle and people:

   SEX -- A Canadian evolutionary biologist suggests females would be
better off keeping males out of their genes; Rosemary Redfield writes
in the journal Nature that a female would be more likely to have
genetically healthier offspring by not mixing her genes with those of
a male. 810 words, by Michael Quintanilla (Times) (l).

   TEXAS-ALAMO -- SAN ANTONIO -- For nearly 90 years, the Daughters of
the Republic of Texas have protected the Alamo, restored it, tended it
and treated it like the most precious real estate in Texas; now they
themselves seem surrounded by critics who want something new, or under
different control, on the site. 1,075 words, by Sue Anne Pressley
(Post) (a). Moved.

   VLADIVOSTOK -- VLADIVOSATOK, Russia -- For 58 years, the Church of
the Most Holy Mother of God was not a place of worship, but an archive
of the Soviet state; it has a history as tragic and grim and now, as
full of hope as Russia's own history in this century. 1,150 words, by
Lee Hockstader (Post) (i). Moved.

   MCENROE -- Purple haze: the many shades of Barneyness. By Colin
McEnroe (Courant) (c).

   ROMANO -- Notes on newsmakers. By Lois Romano (Post) (w).

   Food:

 (All category d.) 

