the West Bank and Gaza cannot go long ignored; the $10 billion U.S.
loan-guarantee program -- just two years ago the single most
contentious issue in U.S.-Israeli relations -- could serve as a vehicle
of conciliation and peacemaking. 1,040 words, by Khalil Jahshan,
William Quandt and Jerome Segal (Post special) (k). Moved.

   RENO -- Unions finally have their day. By Robert Reno (Newsday) (k).

   POST EDITORIAL (moved), TIMES EDITORIAL, SUN EDITORIAL (all k).

   There is no POLLS-COMMENT (Post) feature this week.

   In the nation:

   FEDERAL DIARY -- Reports on the federal workforce. By Mike Causey
(Post) (w).

   Financial:

   HEALTH-RETIRE -- Retirees are increasingly finding themselves on
their own when it comes to health-care coverage; a new survey shows
that most U.S. companies cut employees off from all coverage the
moment they retire, and those that continue to provide coverage shift
most of the cost onto the retiree. 850 words, by Frank Swoboda (Post)
(f). Moved.

   COMPUTERS-DISKS -- WASHN -- We hear endlessly of rapid-fire advances
in microprocessors, but just as important in keeping personal
computing on that ever-upward plane are faster, cheaper,
higher-capacity hard disks; and their gains are just as amazing. 1,100
words, by John Burgess (Post) (f). Moved.

   MARKETING -- Sunglass manufacturers cash in on the culture of cool.
By Bruce Horovitz (Times) (f). Moved

   MONEY-MANAGEMENT -- A growing number of Americans are being caught
up in confusing securities litigation. By Albert B. Crenshaw (Post)
(f). Moved.

