<HEADLINE>
 Editors:
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
   The following features are accompanied by art air-mailed Thursday
from Los Angeles. For missed photos or address changes, call (800)
283-NEWS ext. 77832 or (213) 237-7832.

   TRAVEL-PROVIDENCE-ART -- PROVIDENCE. R.I. -- You're within earshot of
the biggest bell ever cast at Paul Revere's workshop, not far from an
Ivy League university; in colonial days, the city hosted a tea party
to protest Britain's stiff tax; it might sound like Boston, but this
is Providence, the biggest city in little Rhode Island. 1,130 words,
by Steve Silk (Courant) (t) TRAVEL-PROVIDENCE-HOW. Two color photos.

   LUKINS-ART -- Sheila Lukins, half of the Silver Palate team, has
published ``All Around the World Cookbook'' -- her first solo effort;
with the three Silver Palate cookbooks selling more than 5 million
copies, she's hoping to see success follow her book too. 1,400 words,
by Kathie Jenkins (Times) (d). With LUKENS-RECIPES-ART. Five color
photos.

   KITCHEN-ART -- There are so many things you can do with a duck,
including making a salad with duck meat, arugula and an
Asian-influenced dressing. 1,080 words, by Russ Parsons (Times) (d).
One color photo.

   CRAVEN-ART -- WASHINGTON -- Jay Craven, former full-time anti-war
activist, is still leading a charge, but now his venue is a feature
film, ``Where the Rivers Flow North,'' a made-in-Vermont opus funded
mostly by Vermonters and set against a singular time and place in the
state's history. 920 words, by Judith Weinraub (Post) (e). One photo.
Moved.

   LEPROSY-ART -- LOS ANGELES -- Although leprosy, now known as Hansen's
disease, is rare in the United States, there are up to 15 million
cases worldwide; counter to its biblical image, the disease is hard to
transmit but difficult to treat; a look at one of the few treatment
centers in the United States. 700 words, by Glen Justice (Times) (l).
With LEPROSY-TREATMENT-ART. Two color photos.

   BOOKBINDER-ART -- Henry Bookbinders is precisely what the name says,
a place that binds books; it does not print them, publish them, sell
or distribute them; customers must supply the text and Shulem Halpert
supplies the outside. 1,200 words, by Drew Fetherston (Newsday) (l).
One photo.

   CITIES-ART -- LYON, France -- A resurrection of ``city-states'' and
regions is quietly transforming Europe's political and economic
landscape, diminishing the influence of national governments and
redrawing the continental map of power for the 21st century. 1,270
words, by William Drozdiak (Post). With sidebar CITIES-ART-RICH (i).
One map. Moved.

   SAFRICA-BUILD-ART -- KWADABEKA, South Africa -- As South Africa gets
started, no other industry stands to gain more from the political and
economic reconstruction of the country than construction; it remains a
question how much black-owned firms will benefit. 850 words, by
Michelle Singletary (Post) (i). One photo. Moved.
</TEXT>
