<HEADLINE>
 Editors:
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
   Los Angeles Times first-edition Page 1 for Wednesday, June 1, 1994:

   Top of page:

   Col 1: NASA is poised to issue a $1.5 billion contract in coming
weeks to a consortium of every major U.S. commercial airplane and jet
engine company for an ambitious research program leading to a
supersonic jet in regular service by 2005. (SST, will move overnight.)

   Cols 2-6: Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., is indicted on 17 felony
counts of fraud and embezzlement, a far broader set of charges than
many expected, for alleged acts that ranged from taking kickbacks of
government funds to buying cars for his family with public and
campaign money. (With art.)(ROSTY-TIMES, moved.)

   Above fold:

   Col 2: Los Angeles police engage in the second day of a sickout
after rejecting contract terms, leading the mayor to call for
mediation. (COPS, moved.)

   Cols 3-4: Using a plastic automated teller machine card, welfare
recipients and Social Security pensioners without bank accounts would
be able to walk up to an ATM terminal and withdraw their benefit
payments, under a new program unveiled by Vice President Gore.
(BENEFITS-TIMES, moved.)

   Col 6: In many respects, Rep. Dan Rostenkowski's brusque style
during nearly 36 years in Congress has reflected the spoils-system,
take-no-prisoners politics practiced in his hometown of Chicago; so
``Rosty'' was doing what comes naturally when he decided not to holler
``uncle'' and accept a plea bargain. 1,320 words, by William J.
(ROSTY-PROFILE, moved.)

   Below fold:

   Col 3: Citing a crash that killed five people in Santa Ana in
December, the Federal Aviation Administration has adopted a policy
that will require smaller planes to stay farther behind Boeing 757
jetliners to prevent airplane accidents caused by their potentially
hazardous wake turbulence. (FAA-757, moved.)

   Cols 5-6: The Supreme Court gives a boost to the growing number of
cities that enforce curfews for teen-agers when it rejects a challenge
to a Dallas law that generally requires those under 17 to be off the
streets after 11 p.m. on weekdays and midnight on weekends.
(COURT-CURFEW, moved.)

   Bottom of page:

   Cols 1-2: Though defense attorneys are often reviled by a
crime-weary public, they are viewed as being among the more ethical
members of the legal profession. ``The criminal defense bar is far
more honorable to deal with than the civil bar,'' says a longtime
prosecutor. (Will move as part of an upcoming series.)

   Cols 5-6: Police are trying to determine a motive in the shooting
of controversial Nation of Islam figure Khallid Abdul Muhammad.
(ISLAM, moved.)

 Sent: 10:50 p.m. EDT. For questions, call (800) 283-NEWS, ext.
77832.
</TEXT>
